<DOC><DOCNO> AP890818-0086 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1243EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Cambodia     08-18 0190</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Cambodia,0196</SECOND><HEAD>U.N. Fact-Finding Mission Thanks Thailand</HEAD><DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The leader of a United Nationsfact-finding team said Friday that Thailand's help would be neededif an international force is dispatched to Cambodia to help bringpeace to that country.   Lt. Gen. Martin O. Vadset also thanked Prime Minister ChatichaiChoonhavan for assistance during the team's inspection tour of theThai-Cambodian border.   The 15-member team departs Saturday after spending a week insideCambodia and three days at the frontier. The team was dispatched byan international conference in Paris that is trying to bring peaceto Cambodia.   Vadset declined to say what the team would report to theconference Monday.   Vadset's task was to lay the groundwork for a group to monitorthe withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from Cambodia and perhaps act asa peacekeeping force.   A three-party Cambodian coalition is fighting the pro-Hanoigovernment in Cambodia and the Vietnamese army, which invadedCambodia in late 1978. There are fears the fighting could escalateafter the pullout of the Vietnamese.   Without citing details, Vadset said Thailand's assistance wouldbe needed if an international force went into Cambodia.</TEXT></DOC>